   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Love
                           Makes a Man</title></hi>].<note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>Love Makes a Man</title>; or, The Fop's Fortune; A
                              Comedy, In Five Acts; By <ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Colley
                                 Cibber</ref>, Esq. As Performed at the Theatre Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees,
                        and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title
                              level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are
                              Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                                 Lane</ref>, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>, and <ref target="people.html#Haymarket"
                                 >Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers from
                              the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical Remarks, by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald.</ref></title></hi>
                        In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. IX. <hi rendition="#italics">
                           <title>Provoked Wife</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Provoked Husband</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Love Makes a Man</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>She Wou'd and She Wou'd Not</title></hi>. <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title>Careless Husband</title></hi>. London:
                        Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first
                        performance of this play was staged at the <ref
                           target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury Lane</ref> on
                        December 9<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1700. Bernadette D. Woodburn, Laura
                        DeWitt, and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics"
                           >The Criticism Archive</hi>. </note></title>
                  <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>Many a comedy, where the scene is placed in Spain, owes its success to the splendid
               fashion of Spanish dresses, to the bustling spirit of hide and seek in chamber-maids
               and valets, or to the paroxysms of frantic jealousy between lovers.</p>
            <p>The present comedy has claim to public favour upon superior advantages. Here is a
               good fable, variety of occurrence, and, above all, some excellently drawn
               characters.</p>
            <p>The English, in bringing Spaniards upon the stage, have always given them a great
               deal to do, and scarcely any thing to say; at least all they have said has generally
               amounted to nothing. But in "<title>Love makes a Man</title>," the dramatis personæ
               talk as well as act; and speak to a right purpose.</p>
            <p>That there should be mind, as well as manners, attached to the characters of this
               play, will no longer appear extraordinary, when it is considered, that the production
               owes its origin to <ref target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis">Beaumont</ref> and <ref
                  target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref>.<note><hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>Love Makes a Man</title></hi> derives from two plays written by <ref
                     target="people.html#FletcherJohn">John Fletcher</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#MassingerPhilip">Philip Massinger</ref>: <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Elder Brother</title></hi> (1625) and <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Custom of the Country</title></hi> (c.
                  1619-1620). <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Custom of the Country</title></hi>
                  was published in the first <ref target="people.html#BeaumontFrancis"
                     >Beaumont</ref> and <ref target="people.html#FletcherJohn">Fletcher</ref> folio
                  of 1647, while <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Elder Brother</title></hi> was
                  included in the second folio of 1679.</note></p>
            <p>A third author, of no mean repute, exerted his skill in uniting and adorning the
               ancient foundation of this work, (the dramas of "<title>The Elder<pb n="4"/>
                  Brother</title>," and "<title>The Custom of the Country</title>,") according to
               the modern taste, in 1700; and introduced the whole composition to the public under
               the present title; with the additional name affixed, of <ref
                  target="people.html#CibberColley">Colley Cibber</ref>.</p>
            <p>Whilst many a judicious critic boasted of knowing what kind of drama the public ought
               to like; <ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref> was the lucky dramatist
               generally to know what they <hi rendition="#italics">would</hi> like, whether they
               ought or not. If he secured their interest, he defied their understanding; and here,
               in the following scenes, so far he engages the heart in every event, that the head
               does not once reflect upon the improbabilities, or even impossibilities, with which
               the senses are delighted.</p>
            <p>To atone for incident somewhat too extravagant and surprising, the author has brought
               on the stage many very rational and most natural personages.</p>
            <p>The love of learning in the illiterate Don Lewis, is a just trait of disposition,
               though it appears a paradoxical one&#8212;and the endowing of a licentious coxcomb,
               as in Clodio,<note>Don Lewis is the uncle and dear friend of Carlos, a studious young
                  university student turned passionate romantic by the conclusion of the play.
                  Clodio is a "pert coxcomb" and the brother of Carlos.</note> with frankness and
               valour, has been an impartial distribution of virtues and vices, which few authors
               have justice, or rather judgment, enough to bestow upon their copies of mankind.</p>
            <p>The creatures of a writer's brain are much oftener monsters than men; for the wicked
               are seldom more deformed by every ill quality, than the virtuous are out of human
               shape by every good one; and thus both parties are equally irregular, in not agreeing
               with the common order of things.</p>
            <p>But lest from this observation, Carlos should be<pb n="5"/> liable to objection, from
               his wisdom and goodness, it is proper to allow,&#8212;that in him, perfection has
               been so naturally accounted for by the poet, in the description of his youth and
               passion for study, that he appears like one whom temptations have yet never reached,
               rather than like that supernatural being, who can always be proof against them.</p>
            <p>This young student, just from college, argues, reasons, and even preaches without
               either cant or affectation: and the long lessons which he gives to Louisa, in the
               fourth act,<note>Louisa is a "Lady of Quality and Pleasure" who renounces her
                  lifestyle at the end of the play thanks to the lectures of Carlos.</note> are so
               many short sermons addressed to all females: which, combined with Louisa's character,
               will infallibly teach them&#8212;that, though love may sometimes make a man; too
               frequently&#8212;it undoes a woman.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
